The bottom line is: bad news for democracy. Authoritarian forms of
government (or outright dictatorships) do not go out of fashion.
Schleicher manages to whittle away details of the Versailles treaty; the
British-German Naval Agreement is done as in OTL, some settlement can be
reached, way later, as to the Rheinland. Without spending as much as Hitler
on rearmament, an authoritarian German government is viable. Extremists
threaten its stability, but OTOH they also justify its existence as opposed
to true democracy.
This kind of government needs to vent on to some warlike enterprise, as
proven by Italy's Abyssinian stint; but probably Schleicher manages to
channel the hotheads into the Spanish Civil War and possibly some other
minor adventure.
It is possible that some time later, Czechoslovakia implodes, but with less
German pressure from the outside, and therefore it passes away almost
peacefully, relatively speaking.
Thus we can face an Europe in which three kinds of governments coexist and
appear each to have a chance to keep chugging along; authoritarian
right-wing governments, the lone example of the URSS, and democracy. And the
first type might look rather efficient and appealing. This situation might
keep going for a long time; in OTL, minor countries kept or developed
authoritarian governments or dictatorships after WWII, also due to the
Communist threat (Spain, Greece, Turkey). In this ATL, that kind of
government might seem viable even for a major power (Germany, Italy) and
might be in force in other countries, too (Poland, various Eastern European
kingdoms...).

Of course, there is the Chinese affair going on. In OTL, the Japanese made
their moves because the Vichy French could not oppose them, and carried on
also because the Dutch colonies couldn't defend themselves and the British
had their hands full. In this ATL, this isn't true; OTOH, given the Japanese
leadership, some rash decision is always possible. The next big war might be
a colonial war in Asia. it can't be ruled out that if things shake up in the
region, Germany, which has lost all its colonies in 1918 and needs some
action somewhere, offers its help to some of the players, in order to get a
slice. In other words, one also wonders whether the de-colonization process
takes place as in OTL, and as fast.
