I wouldn't be so sure. True, there is not much to be gained in Spain for
this ATL's Germany - but there wasn't a whole lot for our Germany, either,
apart from testing the new hardware and making good propaganda.
OTOH, there is this need of strongly nationalistic regimes to fight (or at
least &quot;fight&quot;) the enemies, be they within or not. What's the point of
ramping up the nationalistic rhetoric if you live peacefully and have no
grudge against anybody?
This goes hand in hand with the authoritarian regimes' need of an enemy, who
justifies the regimes' methods; we can't afford the luxury of democratic
niceties because we're fighting the war on (your preferred fill-in enemy
here).
There is another factor, the one that led to the existence of the Spanish
Division Azul. Schleicher has on his hands these rabid anti-Communists, who
are a pain in the neck at home. Why not use the SCW as a safety valve? In
this ATL, the German &quot;volunteers&quot; might be somewhat closer to real
volunteers.

Is

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; this enough to swing things in favour of the Communists ?
">

No, never. The SCW was not won by the presence of foreign troops as such. If
you want to remove the one foreign ingredient that will crash the
Alzamiento, you have to remove not the troops but the transport aircraft at
the very beginning of the war, which allowed Franco to airlift his reliable
Moroccans from Africa to the Peninsula. Without those aircraft, he's
successful in Africa and the Canarias, but he finds it very difficult to
reinforce his generals in Spain proper. And those were primarily Italian
airplanes, the German ones came after those.
If Schleicher sends not one man, but Mussolini sends his aircraft, Franco
still wins.
