The Italian air force support in the very first days of the Alzamiento was
absolutely invaluable. Not for combat, but for the first troops airlift in
history. Not done very competently (lost a lot of aircraft without enemy
intervention), yet it was the difference between having the Moroccan troops
bottled in Africa and unleashing them in Spain. Anybody could have done
that - but not Franco, and only the Italians were willing to, initially.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Not always. But not even in the same ballpark as the effectiveness of
&gt; German support ... or even Communist support.
">

Well, that depends.
If we look at the committment of whole large units, the Soviets and Germans
did not even show up for the match, there. And the Italian performance was
only marred at Guadalajara, which, for all the propaganda, was at most a
defensive victory for the Republic; for the rest, the Italian divisions were
at least averagely competent or better than that, and, anyway, there is no
comparison because there were no German or Soviet divisions.

As to the training supplied to the Spanish allies, I think the ballpark is
about the same.

As to the hardware. Some of the Soviet and of the German hardware was way
way better, in absolute terms, when compared to Italian hardware. But then
again, much of this assessment is influecned by later (WWII) experiences,
while on the contrary we should assess these toys in the context of the war
they were used in.
Take the German 88mm. Exceptional gun; it could pierce most tanks in WWII;
in the SCW, it could pierce all tanks. Fine, so what? If we look at the SCW
only, the Italian 75mm CK AA gun could do exactly the same - pierce all
tanks. And as to the primary use, AA, they were basically equivalent for the
SCW purposes.
Take the fighters. OK, the German ones were much better than a Fiat CR.32.
So what, as far as the SCW is concerned? The CR.32 did survive encounters
with enemy fighters and did down enemy bombers.
What about the tanks? The German Pz I was only marginally better than a
CV35. A T-26 or a BT-7 were much better, with their superior armor and 45mm
gun - in theory. In practice, in the SCW they were out of action due to
mechanical breakdowns for a very large part of their time, so a running CV35
is much better than an immobilized T-26. And it can scare unsupported, badly
trained infantry just as well as a marginally better Pz I.
So if you want to assess the hardware in absolute terms, yes, your &quot;not in
the same ballpark&quot; definition might apply here and there. But if you assess
it in relative terms, relative to the context it was actually used in, I
don't think it applies.
