Getting back to my contention that the 1945 British were not anxious
to quit India let's see what the Wavell Plan offered:

&quot;The Wavell Plan, which would be effective until the granting of
Indian independence or dominion status, is a modified Cripps Plan.
Under the Cripps Plan, the Viceroy had complete control over defense
and foreign affairs. Under the Wavell Plan, the Viceroy will also
control finance. Under the Cripps Plan, the Assembly could not
overthrow the Government by a vote of censure. Under the Wavell Plan,
the Assembly can overthrow the Government and cause a change of
Executive Council (Cabinet) on any issue except defense, finance or
foreign affairs.&quot;

That's from TIME for May. 21, 1945. The war in Europe was over by that
point but there was no mention of immediately giving India either
independence or dominion status. (Note the wording about independence
or dominion status. Somebody thought they were different things back
then.) Wavell was proposing a plan that would resemble Walter
Ulbricht's DDR except that Ulbricht had more autonomy.

Continuing: &quot;The proposed viceregal control of finance is presumably
due in part to Britain's debtor position to India. Britain now owes
£1,030,000,000 (about $4,500,000,000) in the form of sterling credit
to India. Britain is unable to repay even a small part of the debt
immediately, and does not want India to sell her sterling credit to
the U.S. In time she hopes to pay her debt by sales of export goods to
India.&quot;

So Britain would continue to control the Indian ecomony and would
repay its debts by sales of export goods. Who would determine the
price and value of these marvelous British exports? Not the Indians
I'm sure.

The European war was over when Wavell made his proposal but the
Japanese war continued. How long would it last? Probably 1947 but it
could be going on until 1949 or later. The Indians would of course
have to wait it out.

What if the Wavell Plan fails?

&quot;If the Wavell Plan fails, the Viceroy has the full approval of the
British Cabinet to use the Indian Army to keep order and suppress any
revolt quickly. He has asked for an increase of British officers in
the Indian Army.&quot;
